[[Image:nikulin.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Yuri Nikulin was the first who said: "Make it short, Sklifosovsky"]]
'''Make it short, Sklifosovsky''' is an extremely popular Russian phrase which is used to cut short someone's long speech. This phrase has very little to do with the work of famous Russian physician [[Sklifosovksy]]. This phrase originates from the movie "Caucasian Prisoner". Balbes, a negative character of the movie played by [[Yuri Nikulin]] exclaimed: "Make it short, Sklifosovsky!" to Shurik and his friend, the positive characters, who, after presenting themselves as vaccination nurses, commenced a long lecture about the benefits of immunization. Instead of a vaccine, they injected the bad guys with a sleeping drug. Russians often use this phrase without knowing that it comes from the famous movie. 

== Humor ==
Professor Sklifosovsky got very tired of everybody telling him "Make it short, Sklifosovsky". So, he closed his medical institute and opened a small clinic specialized in circumsision. After that, nobody said to him: "Make it short, Sklifosovsky".{{fact}}

